(Delegated) Allows the connector to read, create, update, and delete the files that the user can access. 

 

FHIR CONNECTOR SETUP 

Adding a FHIR (Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources) data store to Gemini Enterprise allows the AI to search and reason across clinical data like patient records, observations, and encounters. This is done through Vertex AI Search and Conversation. 

Step 1:  FHIR Store should already exist  

Step 2:  Add the FHIR store to Gemini Enterprise  

In Gemini Enterprise Click Data Stores in the left-hand navigation.  Select Healthcare API (FHIR) as your data source. 

A screenshot of a computer

AI-generated content may be incorrect. 

Step 3: Review and Map the Schema 

Vertex AI provides a Google-defined schema for standard FHIR resources. 

Refine Fields: Expand specific resources to verify which fields are "searchable" or "retrievable." 

Add Custom Fields: In case of FHIR Extensions, add them to the schema so that AI can "see" specific data. 

Step 4: Finalize and Index 

Enter a Data Store Name and click Create 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

BIGQUERY CONNECTOR 

This section describes the steps to configure the Gemini Enterprise connector for BigQuery. 

For purpose of current PoC we will be connecting to below BigQuery тАУ 

GCP Project='xykqqimp-shf1-nswe-j57t-6oq8ro ' 

Dataset = `win_quality_agent` 

Tables = win-statements 

Pre-requisite тАУ  

GCP role BigQuery Data Viewer (roles/bigquery.dataViewer) should be granted to user to setup at dataset and table level  

At project level BigQueryJob user role should be granted to the service account used by Gemini Enterprise connector. 

To import data from a source Google Cloud project that's different from the Google Cloud project with the Gemini Enterprise data store, grant the following Identity and Access Management (IAM) roles to theтАпservice-349445209808@gcp-sa-discoveryengine.iam.gserviceaccount.comтАпservice account in the project that contains the Gemini Enterprise data store: 

BigQuery Job User (roles/bigquery.jobUser) 

You can import structured data from BigQuery datasets. Your schema is auto detected. 

After importing, Google recommends that you edit the auto-detected schema to map key properties, such as titles.тАп 

If you select to import structured data with metadata, you include two fields in your BigQuery tables: 

AnтАптАШidтАЩтАпfield to identify the document. If you import structured data without metadata, then theтАптАШidтАЩтАпis generated for you. Including metadata lets you specify the value ofтАпid. 

AтАпjsonDataтАпfield that contains the data.  

 

You can create data stores from BigQuery tables in two ways: 

One-time ingestion: You import data from a BigQuery table into a data store. The data in the data store does not change unless you manuallyтАпrefresh the data. 

Periodic ingestion: You import data from one or more BigQuery tables, and you set up a sync frequency that determines how often the data stores are updated with the most recent data from the BigQuery dataset. 

Import Once from BigQuery  : 

To ingest data from a BigQuery table, use the following steps to create a data store and ingest data using the Google Cloud console. 

To use the Google Cloud console to ingest data from BigQuery, follow these steps: 

In the Google Cloud console, go to theтАпGemini EnterpriseтАпpage. 

Go to theтАпData StoresтАпpage. 

ClickтАпCreate Data Store. 

On theтАпSelect a data sourceтАпpage, selectтАпBigQuery. 

SelectтАпwhat kind of data you are importing. Select тАШStructured Data ImportтАЩ and тАШBigQuery Table with your own schemaтАЩ option. 

In case specialized data import we can select one of the following options- 

Media тАУ BigQuery table with structured media data 

Unstructured тАУ BigQuery table with metadata 

Healthcare тАУ BigQuery table with structured healthcare data 

ClickтАпOne time. 

In theтАпBigQuery pathтАпfield, clickтАпBrowse, select a table that you haveтАпprepared for ingesting, and then clickтАпSelect. Alternatively, enter the table location directly in theтАпBigQuery pathтАпfield. 

ClickтАпContinue. 

If you are doing one-time import of structured data: 

Map fields to key properties. 

If there are important fields missing from the schema, useтАпAdd new fieldтАпto add them. 

For more information, seeтАпAbout auto-detect and edit. 

ClickтАпContinue. 

Choose a region for your data store. 

Enter a name for your data store. 

ClickтАпCreate. 

To check the status of your ingestion, go to theтАпData StoresтАпpage and click your data store name to see details about it on itsтАпDataтАпpage. When the status column on theтАпActivityтАпtab changes fromтАп in progressтАпtoтАпImport completed, the ingestion is complete. 

Depending on the size of your data, ingestion can take several minutes to several hours. 

 

Periodic Ingestion from BigQuery  : 

The following procedure describes how to create a BigQueryтАпdata storeтАпthat periodically syncs data from a BigQuery dataset. If your dataset has multiple tables, you can add them to the BigQuery data store you are creating. Each table you add is referred to as an entity. Gemini Enterprise creates a separate data store for each entity. Therefore, when you create the data store using the Google Cloud console, you get a collection of data stores representing these ingested data entities. 

Data from the dataset is synced periodically to the entity data stores. You can specify synchronization daily, every three days, or every five days. 

To create a data store that periodically syncs data from a BigQuery dataset to Gemini Enterprise, follow these steps: 

In the Google Cloud console, go to theтАпGemini EnterpriseтАпpage. 

In the navigation menu, clickтАпData Stores. 

ClickтАпCreate Data Store. 

On theтАпSourceтАпpage, selectтАпBigQuery. 

Select the kind of data that you are importing. 

Click onтАпPeriodic. 

Select theтАпSync frequency, how often you want the Gemini Enterprise connector to sync with the BigQuery dataset. You can change the frequency later. 

In theтАпBigQuery dataset pathтАпfield, clickтАпBrowse, select the dataset that contains the tables that you haveтАпprepared for ingesting. Alternatively, enter the table location directly in theтАпBigQuery pathтАпfield. The format for the path isтАпprojectname.datasetname. 

In theтАпTables to syncтАпfield, clickтАпBrowse, and then select a table that contains the data that you want for your data store. 

Note:тАпMake sure that the data in the tables matches the kind of data that you selected in step 5. 
If there is a mismatch you won't know until one of the following happens: 

You get errors when the connector tries to import data. 

You see unexpected search results. This happens if the selected type was structured but should have been unstructured or structured with metadata. The data is imported, but the content URL or metadata is not recognized and is treated as a string. 

After a data store is created, you cannot update the selected BigQuery tables. To update the table list, you must delete the existing data store and create a new one. 

If there are additional tables in the dataset that you want to use for data stores, clickтАпAdd tableтАпand specify those tables too. 

ClickтАпContinue. 

Choose a region for your data store, enter a name for your data connector, and clickтАпCreate. 

You have now created a data connector, which will periodically sync data with the BigQuery dataset. And, you have created one or more entity data stores. The data stores have the same names as the BigQuery tables. 

To check the status of your ingestion, go to theтАпData StoresтАпpage and click your data connector name to see details about it on itsтАпDataтАпpage >тАпData ingestion activityтАпtab. When the status column on theтАпActivityтАпtab changes fromтАпin progressтАпtoтАпsucceeded, the first ingestion is complete. 

Depending on the size of your data, ingestion can take several minutes to several hours. 

After you set up your data source and import data the first time, the data store syncs data from that source at a frequency that you select during setup. About an hour after the data connector is created, the first sync occurs. The next sync then occurs around 24тАпhours, 72тАпhours, or 120тАпhours later. 

Create Enterprise Search App and attach Data Store тАУ 

In the Google Cloud console, go to theтАпGemini Enterprise page. 

On theтАпAppsтАпpage, clickтАпCreate app. 

In theтАпApp nameтАпfield, enter a name for your app. 

To update the automatically generated appтАпID, clickтАпEdit. The app ID cannot be updated after you create the app. 

In theтАпChoose a locationтАпsection, select aтАпmulti-region. Use the defaultтАпglobal (Global)тАпmulti-region unless you need to restrict your data to a specific geography. 

To provide your company's external name, expandтАпAdvanced options. In theтАпCompany nameтАпfield, enter your company's external name (for e.g. Optum) omitting suffixes such as Inc or LLC. This helps the LLM identify the company the app represents. 

ClickтАпCreate. 

Once App is created, we can connect it to existing data store by following the steps below 

In the Google Cloud console, go to theтАпGemini Enterprise page. 

From the navigation menu, clickтАпApps. 

Select the Gemini Enterprise app where you want to connect your data store. 

From the navigation menu of the app, clickтАпConnected data sources. 

ClickтАпAdd existing data storesтАпand select your data store. 

ClickтАпConnect. 

 

User Authorization тАУ 

To successfully connect and use data stores with your Gemini Enterprise app, ensure that you have authorized Gemini Enterprise to access data from your data store. 

In the Google Cloud console, go to theтАпGemini Enterprise page. 

From the navigation menu, clickтАпApps. 

Select the Gemini Enterprise app where you have connected your data store. 

 

Click the web app URL or copy it to open it in a new tab. 

Select тАШManage Your DataтАЩ 

Screen displaying manage data. 

Authorize your Data Store тАУ 

For data stores with actions configured, clickтАпEnable actionsтАпand then sign in to authorize your data store. 

For search-only data stores, clickтАпAuthorizeтАпand then sign in to authorize your data store. 

Screen displaying options to authorize data store connections. 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

GraphQL API & FHIR CONNECTOR USING API 

The PES GraphQL Connector converts the PES API into a natural language interface powered by Vertex AI Agent Engine. 

Stakeholders can type queries like тАЬShow ExaminerS practitionersтАЭ and receive live practitioner details (NPI, Name, Specialties, Credentials, Status) within seconds. 

The solution leverages: 

Agent Development Kit (ADK) 

Vertex AI 

OAuth2 Client Credentials flow for secure API access 

 

Step 1: Authentication Layer 

Purpose: Enable secure access to the UHG PES API using OAuth2 client credentials. 

Key Functions: 

Generate access token via OAuth2 flow 

Secure client ID and client secret handling via Secret Manager 

Add the bearer token to subsequent API requests 

Rectangle 11, TextboxRectangle 10, TextboxRectangle 9, Textbox 

 

 

 

 

A computer screen with many green text 

 

Step 2: GraphQL Query Layer 

Purpose: Execute authenticated GraphQL queries against PES practitioner endpoint.    

API Endpoint:тАпhttps://api-stg.uhg.com/api/provider/demographics/practitioner/1.0.0 

  Method: POST (application/json) 

  Query Returns: NPI, Name, Specialties, Credentials, Status 

  Sample Response: (Raw JSON): 

{ 

  "response": [ 

    { 

      "npi": "123...", 

      "name": "Dr. Smith", 

      "specialties": ["Cardiology"] 

    } 

  ] 

} 

 

Step 3: ADK Agent Logic 

Purpose: Convert natural language queries into GraphQL tool calls and return a human-readable response. 

Agent Configuration:  

  Agent: pes_agent  

  Model: "gemini-2.0-flash-exp", 

   Processing Flow: 

Parse user intent 

Invoke pes_search tool 

Execute GraphQL query 

Retrieve response 

Format structured, human-friendly output 

Step 4: GCS Query Storage 

Purpose: Store GraphQL queries externally to enable zero-code updates. 

Permissions:тАпroles/storage.objectViewerтАпon bucket 

Upload the query inside GCS bucket. 

A screenshot of a computer 

Benefits: 

Dynamic query management 

Version control capability 

No redeployment required for query changes 

 

