Architecture Diagram 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Best Practices 

Foundational Practices 

1. Centralize connectors in one controlled project 

2. Apply least-privilege IAM 

3. Use enterprise-managed service accounts 

4. Rotate credentials regularly 

5. Identify PII and apply redaction / masking 

6. Enable logging  

7. Monitor Connector usage  

  

Microsoft Outlook: 

1. Avoid full mailbox access 

2. Use Mail.Read instead of Mail.ReadWrite 

3. Monitor Large Attachment extraction  

4. Avoid syncing entire historical mailbox 

5. Define time-window filtering 

6. Limit attachment ingestion size 

  

SharePoint Connector  

 1. Grant access only to specific Sites or Libraries 

2, Use SharePoint group-based access 

3. Capture: 

Document version 

Owner 

Created/Modified timestamp 

4. Use metadata for context grounding 

  

OneDrive Connector  

1.Avoid entire organizational drive access 

2.Connect only approved shared folders	 

3.Set file size limits 

4.Exclude binary-heavy content unless required 

  

BigQuery Connector 

1. Grant only: roles/bigquery.dataViewer roles to the users to control updating the records  

2. Avoid Write permissions 

3. Avoid bigquery.admin 

4. Use final datasets instead of raw tables 

5. Use views instead of tables 

6. Use partitioned and clustered tables  

7. Define column descriptions in Bigquery at table level before setting up the connector to ensure the AI understands business semantics instead of raw data types 

8.Use тАЬAdditional LLM instructionsтАЭ to hardcode agent persona, formatting and output rules for a consistent user experience. 

9.Implement row level security by configuring the acl_info column and enabling ACLs during datastore setup to enforce data privacy 

 

  

GraphQL Connector: 

1.Store all credentials in Secret Manager 

2.Rotate secrets and OAuth tokens regularly 

3.Assign least privilege IAM roles to all service accounts 

4.Never log sensitive user data or PII 

5.Log only high-level metadata (e.g., request type, count, status) 

6.Use HTTPS endpoints consistently 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

PESAgent Deployment Guide:  

Purpose 

This document explains how a developer can: 

Download the PES Agent code from Git 

Open and edit the code in Visual Studio Code (VS Code) 

Add or modify files if required 

Commit and push changes 

Trigger automatic deployment via GitHub 

Note: Deployment is fully automated. 
Any push to the pes-agent branch triggers deployment automatically. 

Prerequisites 

Before starting, ensure the following are installed on your system: 

Git  

Visual Studio Code (VS Code)  

GitHub Access  

You must have access to the PES Agent repository 

 

Step 1: Download (Clone) the Code from GitHub 

Open VS Code 

Open the Terminal inside VS Code  

Menu тЖТ Terminal тЖТ New Terminal 

Navigate to a folder where you want the code:  

Python 

cd <your-local-folder> 

Clone the repository:  

Terminal 

git clone https://github.com/optum-eeps/epgeminienterprise-graphql.git 

Navigate into the project folder:  

Terminal 

cd <repo-name> 

You now have the code locally. 

Step 2: Open the Project in VS Code 

In VS Code:  

Click File тЖТ Open Folder 

Select the cloned repository folder 

 

You should see files such as:  

agent.py 

pes_tool.py 

Requirements.txt 

agent_engine_config.json 

.github/workflows/deploy-agent-engine.yaml 

 

Step 3: Create or Switch to the pes-agent Branch 

All deployments happen from the pes-agent branch. 

Check current branch:  

Terminal 

git branch 

If not already on pes-agent, switch:  

Terminal 

git checkout pes-agent 

If the branch does not exist locally:  

Terminal 

git checkout -b pes-agent origin/pes-agent 

You are now on the correct deployment branch. 

Step 4: Make Code Changes 

You can now: 

Edit existing files 

Add new files 

Update logic as required 

Common files you may edit: 

agent.py тАУ Agent behaviour and instructions 

pes_tool.py тАУ API / GraphQL logic 

agent_engine_config.json тАУ Environment configuration 

requirements.txt тАУ Python dependencies 

Add a new file (if required) 

RightтАСclick in VS Code Explorer 

Click New File 

Name the file and add code 

Save the file 

All changes are local until committed. 

Step 5: Check What Changed 

Before committing, review changes: 

Terminal 

git status 

This shows: 

Modified files 

New files 

Deleted files (if any) 

(Optional) View detailed differences: 

Terminal 

git diff 

Step 6: Add Changes to Git 

Stage all changes: 

Terminal 

git add . 

This prepares files for commit. 

Step 7: Commit the Changes 

Create a commit with a clear message: 

Terminal 

git commit -m "Updated PES agent logic" 

The changes are now saved locally in Git. 

Step 8: Push Changes to GitHub 

Push to the pes-agent branch: 

Terminal 

git push origin pes-agent 

This automatically triggers deployment. 

Step 9: Deployment (Automatic) 

Once the push completes: 

GitHub Actions starts automatically 

The workflow:  

Builds the agent 

Validates configuration 

Deploys to Agent Engine 

No manual deployment steps are required 

 

Step 10: Check Deployment Status (Optional) 

Open the GitHub repository in browser 

Go to Actions tab 

Click the latest workflow run 

Verify status:  

тЬЕ Green = Successful deployment 

тЭМ Red = Deployment failed (check logs) 

 

 

 

 
